{
  "action_id": "52",
  "action_title": "Reintroduce laboratory-reared bumblebee colonies to the wild",
  "key_messages": "Key Messages:\nSeven replicated trials have monitored the success of laboratory-reared colonies of bumblebees introduced to the environment. In four of the trials (three in the UK, one in Canada) colonies were left to develop until new queens were produced or the founding queen died. In two of these (both in the UK), the numbers of queens/colony were very low or zero. In two trials, good numbers of new queens were produced.\nRates of social parasitism by cuckoo bees Bombus [Psithyrus] spp. in colonies released to the wild are variable. Two replicated trials in Canada and the UK found high rates (25-66% and 79% respectively). The UK trial showed that parasitism was reduced by placing colonies in landscapes with intermediate rather than very high nectar and pollen availability, late, rather than early in the season. Five other replicated trials reported no social parasites. We have not found evidence to compare rates of parasitism in artificial nest boxes with the rate in natural nests.\nTwo replicated trials examined the effects of supplementary feeding for bumblebee colonies placed in the field. One, in Canada, found supplementary feeding improved the reproductive success of captive-reared colonies, but did not reduce their parasite load. The other trial, in the USA, found supplementary feeding did not increase colony productivity.\nOne small scale trial in Norway showed that colonies of the buff-tailed bumblebee B. terrestris prefer to forage more than 100 m from their nest sites."
}

{
  "query": "What is the state of the evidence regarding the success of captive rearing and subsequent reintroduction of bumblebees into the wild?",
  "relevant_summary": "Evidence from 22 trials across 13 countries documents methods and outcomes of captive rearing of bumblebees, including confining mated queens alone or with workers, using honey bee workers or male pupae, and CO2 anaesthetisation; outcomes vary by species and method, with one trial noting declining queen weight over four years in Bombus terrestris (50). For several North American species now declining, some trials induced queens (e.g., B. vagans) to rear adults in captivity, while others found queens laid eggs but larvae failed to reach adulthood (e.g., B. fervidus; similar patterns reported for B. affinis and B. pensylvanicus) (50). Captive-rearing success is influenced by diet and husbandry: colonies fed freshly frozen, higher-protein pollen produced larger, better-surviving queens and more offspring; artificial light regimes (8h light:16h dark) shortened time to egg-laying; hibernation at 4\u20135\u00b0C for 45 days enhanced egg-laying and colony formation though produced smaller colonies, and survival was higher for queens >0.6 g and hibernated \u22644 months (50). Seven replicated field trials of reintroducing laboratory-reared colonies report mixed outcomes: in some trials good numbers of new queens were produced, while in others queen output was very low or zero (52). Social parasitism after release was variable and sometimes high (25\u201366% and 79% in two trials), with one UK trial showing lower parasitism when colonies were placed in intermediate-resource landscapes and later in the season; five other trials reported no social parasites (52). Supplementary feeding had mixed effects post-release: it improved reproductive success in one Canadian trial but did not increase productivity in a USA trial (52). A small-scale Norwegian trial found released B. terrestris colonies foraged mostly >100 m from nests (52). Overall, the evidence shows captive rearing protocols can produce viable colonies in some species and conditions, but post-release success in producing new queens and avoiding parasitism is inconsistent across trials (50, 52).",
  "action_ids": [
    "50",
    "52"
  ]
}

