  "query": "What actions, other than providing bare ground, can be taken to create or enhance nesting sites for various bee species?",
  "relevant_summary": "Provide artificial nest sites for solitary bees using cut hollow stems or tubes, blocks of wood drilled with holes, or wooden boxes; these designs were readily occupied in many trials, including by some endangered species and a newly discovered species, though one trial recorded no use by bees [47]. Nest box placement should be within 150\u2013600 m of foraging resources, based on replicated experiments in Germany [47, 80]. Materials matter: reed stems and wooden grooved-board nest boxes produced more bees per nest than several other types, while plastic-lined holes or plastic/paper tubes were much less productive due to parasitism or mould; for Centris analis, cardboard straws in drilled wooden holes were more productive than stacked grooved boards [47, 80]. Repeated provision at a site can increase the number of occupied solitary bee nests over three years, and increases in local population size or emerging red mason bees were reported when nest boxes were provided [47, 80]. Reported occupancy rates for solitary bee nest boxes ranged from 1% to 26% of available cavities, with 4.6\u201333 bee species recorded using boxes across studies; two trials of bumblebee nest boxes found very low uptake (\u22642%) [80]. Monitoring is important because nest boxes can experience brood mortality and parasitism, with reported mortality and parasitism rates varying widely across studies [47]. Some boxes in California were more commonly occupied by introduced earwigs and introduced leafcutter bees than native bees [47].",
