{
  "query": "What evidence exists for the effectiveness of bee conservation actions in human-managed, non-agricultural settings like gardens, road verges, and areas under power lines?",
  "relevant_summary": "Across human-managed greenspaces and linear infrastructures, multiple studies report effects on Lepidoptera. Restoring or maintaining species-rich vegetation on road/rail verges increased butterfly and moth richness and diversity when verges were restored/sown with native wildflowers, had more larval host plants, more plant species, or more flowering plants; wide verges had higher richness; and verges and land under power lines managed by mowing once or twice a year, or not at all, had similar butterfly richness to remnant prairies [3854]. Abundance increased on restored/sown verges with more larval host plants; wide verges had higher abundance; and verges and land under power lines managed by mowing once or twice a year, or not at all, had similar butterfly abundance to remnant prairies [3854]. Mortality risk was lower on restored prairie verges than on non-native grass verges, fewer butterflies were killed where verges were mown less frequently or later in summer, but more dead butterflies and moths were found on roads with tall meadow verges than on frequently mown short-grass or wooded verges; monarch caterpillar parasite load on verges mown once or twice a year was similar to prairies [3854]. Restricting or stopping herbicide use was associated with greater butterfly richness and abundance and lower mortality risk on restored roadside prairies, while transmission lines (road verges and power lines) that were neither sprayed nor mown had similar total butterfly richness and abundance but greater abundance of some species (northern pearl crescent and pearl crescent) compared to sprayed and mown lines [3899]. Altering mowing regimes showed that less frequently mown or unmown urban greenspaces had higher butterfly/moth richness and diversity, unmown public parks and road verges/land under power lines had higher abundance of all adult butterflies or of some species, late-summer mowing increased ringlet numbers, and less frequent or later mowing reduced butterfly roadkill; one study found richness did not differ on road verges/under power lines across management, butterflies occurred on both mown/unmown verges but on mown verges were recorded only where hay was removed, and less frequently mown urban grasslands were more often occupied by scarce copper [3841].",
