{
  "query": "How do the impacts of planting floral resources for bees differ when implemented at a local patch scale versus a wider landscape scale?",
  "relevant_summary": "At the local patch scale, sown flower strips and planted floral patches consistently attract substantial numbers of foraging wild bees, often including many bumblebees, with recorded species richness ranging from 8 to 35 on phacelia-dominated patches (Action ID: 17). Local effects can include enhanced reproductive success for target species (e.g., bigleaf lupine patches increased Osmia lignaria reproduction in Canadian orchards) (Action ID: 17). However, some studies found limited spillover into the surrounding farmland, with no increases in bee numbers or species richness 50\u20131,500 m away from planted patches, and relatively few solitary bees nesting on set\u2011aside fields sown with phacelia or clover (Action ID: 17). At the wider landscape scale, long\u2011tongued bumblebee abundance on field margins was positively correlated with the number of \u2018pollen and nectar\u2019 agri\u2011environment agreements within 10 km grid squares, indicating landscape\u2011level gains where floral resources are increased across many sites (Action IDs: 21, 362). Landscape context can also modulate local patch attractiveness, with perennial leguminous herbs proving more attractive to bumblebees in more arable landscapes (Action ID: 17).",
